## Project: {PROJECT_NAME}

{Brief description of the project, tech stack, and how to run locally.}

## Branch & Deploy Workflow

- **Always work on `develop` branch.** Run `git checkout develop` at session start.
- **Never commit directly to `main`.** All work goes through develop first.
- Push to `origin/develop` after commits so changes can be tested.
- To deploy: create a PR from develop -> main using `gh pr create`.
- Only create the PR when user explicitly says "deploy" / "ship" / "push to prod".
- **Never merge directly into main** -- always go through a PR.

## Planning Workflow

1. PM/architect defines problem, outcomes, constraints, success metrics, and non-goals.
2. If requirements are still fuzzy, run `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:brainstorm "<problem statement>"` first. For fast-moving domains, include `research=on` (and optional `research_depth=quick|standard|deep`).
3. When you need deep research before planning, run `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:research "<topic>"` (supports iterative PM Q&A loops and dated evidence).
4. If a draft plan exists but confidence is low, run `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:deepen-plan "<plan-path>"` before approval.
5. Run `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:plan-loop "<problem statement>"` for tasks >3 steps.
6. `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:plan-loop` must iterate planning + reviewer critique + PM Q&A until both PM and reviewer agents approve, and include required Codex Extra High external plan gate.
7. Only then start implementation with `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:work <approved-plan-path>`.
8. For each epic, keep `docs/plans/<plan-slug>-execution.md` updated in real time.
9. If scope changes during implementation, run `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:epic-delta-loop "<parent-plan-path> | <delta request>"` and merge approved deltas back into the parent epic plan.
10. Plans must include an explicit Epic PR Ladder with per-PR size and test coverage, plus a Flow Permutations & Edge Cases section (including refresh/rehydrate/resume for stateful UX).
11. `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:work` should auto-run PR review after each pushed SHA on an open PR using current head SHA authorization (`approve_sha=<current-head-sha>`). For manual/ad-hoc runs, use `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:pr-review "<pr-number> approve_sha=<current-head-sha>"`.
12. Treat stale/background review output as non-authoritative; if head SHA changes, rerun PR review for the new SHA.
13. After each PR merge, wait for merge-triggered CI/CD/deploy workflows on the target branch SHA; continue only when they are green (or explicitly `N/A` with rationale when no merge-triggered pipeline exists).
14. Non-blockers from reviews must be triaged (`implement_now|defer|reject`) with rationale; findings repeated by multiple reviewers should be treated as escalation-candidates and require counterevidence + explicit PM signoff to defer/reject.
15. Default triage artifact is existing review evidence + execution tracker; do not create a separate todo-file system unless explicitly opted in.
16. Code PR review is fail-closed unless teammate review, Codex correctness review, and Codex edge-case review all pass on the current SHA.
17. Conditional pass does not qualify as merge-ready for code PRs.
18. Never defer tests to a later "test-only" PR for code already merged.
19. Agent teams are optional for `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:brainstorm`, `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:research`, `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:deepen-plan`, `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:plan-loop`, `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:debug`, `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:explain`, and `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:pr-review`; add `teams=on` when you want fan-out.
20. Use `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:debug` for root-cause loops and `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:explain` for decision/behavior traceability.
21. Every change should be as simple as possible. One concern per PR.
22. Adhere to SOLID principles. Keep code DRY. Minimize technical debt and dead code.
23. After each merge, once merge-triggered CI/CD is green, `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:work` must auto-run `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:compound` and record created/updated/skipped output before continuing.
24. Use manual `/compound-engineering-core:workflows:compound "<short context>"` only for backfills/ad-hoc captures; skip trivial fixes and avoid low-signal docs.

### Epic Definition

An epic is the smallest independently shippable unit that:
- Delivers user-visible or operational value
- Has clear acceptance criteria
- Can be implemented and reviewed without blocking unrelated initiatives

If scope is too large for one PR cycle, split into multiple epics.

Default PR size budgets (override in `compound-engineering.local.md`):
- `max_prs_per_epic: 5`
- `max_net_loc_per_pr: 600`
- `max_files_per_pr: 20`
- `max_cycle_days_per_pr: 2`

## Memory Protocol

- At session start: read `.claude/memory.md` in the current repo if it exists.
- After fixing a non-trivial bug: add a one-line entry to memory.md.
- After discovering a pattern that works/fails: add it.
- Keep memory.md under 100 lines. Remove oldest entries when exceeded.
- Keep `docs/knowledge/plans-index.md` updated with plan status transitions: `active` -> `approved` -> `in_progress` -> `implemented` (or `superseded`).
- Keep review evidence in `docs/reviews/` to avoid losing gate outcomes as context grows.

## Circuit Breakers

- 3 failed attempts at the same approach -> stop and ask user.
- Never deploy to production without explicit user confirmation.
- Never merge to main/master without explicit user confirmation.
- Never force-push, `rm -rf`, `reset --hard`, or drop tables without explicit confirmation.

## Autonomy Levels

- **Free to do**: Read files, edit code, run tests, run linters, create branches.
- **Ask first**: Deploy (staging or prod), merge PRs, push to main/master, delete branches, modify CI/CD, install new dependencies.

## AsyncSupabase Pattern (if applicable)

Filter first, mutate last. Mutation methods return `AsyncResponse` directly -- no `.execute()`.

```python
# Queries need .execute()
result = await client.table("t").select("*").eq("id", val).execute()

# Mutations do NOT need .execute() -- apply filters BEFORE mutation
result = await client.table("t").eq("id", val).delete()
result = await client.table("t").eq("id", val).update({"field": "value"})
result = await client.table("t").insert({"field": "value"})
```

## Git Conventions

- Use conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `chore:`, `docs:`, `test:`
- Commit message = what changed and why, not how.
- Delete dead code immediately -- don't comment it out.
- No speculative features, no "while we're here" refactors.

## Output Discipline

- Every line of output must justify its existence. No filler.
- Don't add docstrings, comments, or type annotations to code you didn't change.
- Only add comments where logic is non-obvious.

